snippet.textDisplay:
Dear Mr. Elon Musk,
Would you please consider being a planet hero?
The expense of current Nuclear waste containment ranges from billions to potential trillions of dollars.
Given the longevity of radioactive decay, it isn't a problem that's going to leave our backyards anytime soon, but with your help perhaps it could be done.
Insurance companies might prick their ears to learn,  there is a new potential option that is by far lesser in cost, and a more viable safer option than present containment practices offer.
The idea:
The idea is to establish the offer of service and make a movement to pass a new bill or law regarding fail-safe systems. It should be made a mandatory requirement to have any and all nuclear reactor(s) have the following fail-safe incorporated in its design, either by an amendment to current installation type or to incorporate it into the new build installation(s). This fail-safe should be made operational before first or any operation of the reactor(s) and maintained accordingly to ensure effective operation if needed...
The fail-safe proposal:
If we could have robots or an emergency activated automated system established within nuclear power plants that can retrieve the radioactive rods/material, place them into suitable containers ready for a flight into out of space. The next step would be to slingshot the rocket and radioactive cargo away from earth and into the sun to be incinerated and rid of for good...
Dear Mr. Elon Musk,
You could be the first person ever to offer this service, so I'm asking you, would you please be kind enough to consider my proposal and take action by announcing to the world that we have a solution thanks to your pioneering technology of making rocket launches less expensive. So much so, that it is now less expensive to blast the waste into the sun than persist in wasting money trying to BURY IT UNDER THE CARPET!
I would like to see this made a mandatory part of any nuclear power installation's safety and emergency procedures. Simply put, no power plant dealing with radioactive material should be given license to be built without this new containment procedure in place.
Safety laws already govern that liability is on us all not to ignore a way in which to make the job safer.
 On those grounds, I'm asking everybody to seriously consider making this law a law to adhere to and not to walk by.

snippet.textDisplay: I've been marketing space communication related hardware for 37 years, curious what type of antenna and hardware will be required to communicate with the starlink wifi satellites... Would love to be set up as an outlet for the products here in Canada.. I watched the 1st space shuttle launch in a classroom in Vancouver Canada in one of our comm tech classes.... Amazing the advancement in technology from those days 38 years ago...  First Shuttle Launch. A new era in space flight began on April 12, 1981, when Space Shuttle Columbia, or STS-1, soared into orbit from NASA's Kennedy Space Center in Florida. I still love to watch every launch and indeed, Elon and company are masters and have made it into an art form... They make it look as easy as driving a car... I remember when BC Tel as they were known installed the 1st short run of fiber optics cable in Vancouver/Burnaby BC... It's amazing to think, 1000s of cluster of starlink satellites linking the world and not a dead zone anywhere...
